05575nam a22007335i 9780824851347DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248513477 a10.1515/97808248513472doi  a(DE-B1597)483896  a(OCoLC)890146613  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBQ8720b.C55 2014eb 7aREL0070102bisacsh04a294.3/9262231 aChilson, Clark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSecrecy’s Power :bCovert Shin Buddhists in Japan and Contradictions of Concealment /cClark Chilson; ed. by Paul L. Swanson. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (235 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNanzan Library of Asian Religion and Culture ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tConventions -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: Secrecy in the History of Covert Shin Buddhists -- t1. Secrecy Causes Criticism and Persecution -- t2. Secrecy Preserves and Transforms -- tPart Two: Concealment in Contemporary Urahōmon -- t3. Secrecy Alters by Separating and Joining -- t4. Secrecy Creates Dilemmas -- t5. Secrecy Gives Order -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Japanese Characters -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShin has long been one of the most popular forms of Buddhism in Japan. As a devotional tradition that emphasizes gratitude and trust in Amida Buddha, it is thought to have little to do with secrecy. Yet for centuries, Shin Buddhists met on secluded mountains, in homes, and in the backrooms of stores to teach their hidden doctrines and hold clandestine rites. Among their adherents was D. T. Suzuki’s mother, who took her son to covert Shin meetings when he was a boy. Even among Shin experts, covert followers were relatively unknown; historians who studied them claimed they had disappeared more than a century ago. A serendipitous encounter, however, led to author Clark Chilson’s introduction to the leader of a covert Shin Buddhist group—one of several that to this day conceal the very existence of their beliefs and practices. In Secrecy’s Power Chilson explains how and why they have remained hidden. Drawing on historical and ethnographic sources, as well as fieldwork among covert Shin Buddhists in central Japan, Secrecy’s Power introduces the histories, doctrines, and practices of different covert Shin Buddhists. It shows how, despite assumptions to the contrary, secrecy has been a significant part of Shin’s history since the thirteenth century, when Shinran disowned his eldest son for claiming secret knowledge. The work also demonstrates how secrecy in Shin has long been both a source of conflict and a response to it. Some covert Shin Buddhists were persecuted because of their secrecy, while others used it to protect themselves from persecution under rulers hostile to Shin. Secrecy’s Power is a groundbreaking work that makes an important contribution to our knowledge on secrecy and Shin Buddhism. Organized around the various consequences concealment has had for covert Shin Buddhists, it provides new insights into the power of secrecy to produce multiple effects—even polar opposite ones. It also sheds light on ignored corners of Shin Buddhism to reveal a much richer, more diverse, and more contested tradition than commonly is understood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSecrecyxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aShin (Sect)zJapanxCustoms and practices. 0aShin BuddhistszJapan. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh1 aSwanson, Paul L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-201